<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14087">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Electricity.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13053">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Demonstrate that you know how to respond to electrical emergencies by
      doing the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13053 mb-requirement-id-13054">
        (a) Explain how to turn off power for a particular circuit and the whole
        house in the event of an emergency. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/YJ3ky3VSGgQ" target="_blank"
          >How To Turn Off Your Home's Electrical Power Supply (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/bvw6D76xfyE" target="_blank"
          >Turning Off Electricity at the Circuit Box (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13053 mb-requirement-id-13055">
        (b) Demonstrate how to rescue a person touching a live wire in the home.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13053 mb-requirement-id-13056">
        (c) Describe how to safely get out of a car in an accident if you
        suspect a utility wire is on the car. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/jpZUaM6kbVg" target="_blank"
          >Electric Safety: What To Do if a Downed Wire Falls on Your Car
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13053 mb-requirement-id-13057">
        (d) Show how to render first aid to a person who is unconscious from an
        apparent electrical shock. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/OEtsLDZTDcA" target="_blank"
          >Electrical Hazards and Emergency Situations (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13053 mb-requirement-id-13058">
        (e) Show how to treat an electrical burn.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13053 mb-requirement-id-13076">
        (f) Explain what to do in the event of an electrical fire. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/b-kYm1Yiazw" target="_blank"
          >5 Steps To Put Out an Electrical Fire (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13053 mb-requirement-id-13077">
        (g) Explain what to do if caught out in the open during an electrical
        storm. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/11jsqsGeQiY" target="_blank"
          >Lightning Safety: How To Protect Yourself, What To Avoid (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/E-A478dbTh8" target="_blank"
          >Frankenweenie Clip (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13069">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Complete an electrical home safety inspection of your home, using the
      checklist found in the <em>Electricity</em> merit badge pamphlet or one
      approved by your counselor. Discuss what you find with your counselor.
      <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Electricity/Electrical%20Safety%20Checklist.docx.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >Electrical Fire Safety Checklist (PDF)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13070">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Make a simple electromagnet and use it to show magnetic attraction and
      repulsion. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/v8mPY1Ee32s" target="_blank"
        >How To Make an Electromagnet! (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13071">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13071 mb-requirement-id-13078">
        (a) Explain the difference between direct current and alternating
        current, the advantages and disadvantages of each, and give a practical
        example of the use of each type. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/J8qVLb3a35s" target="_blank"
          >AC and DC Current Explained (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13071 mb-requirement-id-13079">
        (b) Explain three ways that electricity is produced. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ZtTFe4rxw48" target="_blank"
          >Generating Electricity (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13072">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      Make a simple drawing to show how a battery and an electric bell work.
      Describe the purpose of each of the components. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/QSWvekUUV3w" target="_blank"
        >How an Electric Bell Works / 3D Animation (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/8S-PHo156U4" target="_blank"
        >How Do Electric Bells Work? (3D Animation | Electromagnets) (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13073">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13073 mb-requirement-id-13080">
        (a) Define what overloading an electric circuit means. Tell what you
        have done to make sure your home circuits are not overloaded. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/T3Ngrw6MYTg" target="_blank"
          >Overloaded Circuit (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13073 mb-requirement-id-13081">
        (b) Determine if there is an overload on a branch circuit by either
        getting the current draw from all the equipment plugged into the circuit
        or use the power equation to calculate the current draws.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13073 mb-requirement-id-13082">
        (c) Explain why a fuse blows and a circuit breaker trips. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9q31SzeVjP0" target="_blank"
          >Circuit Breaker Keeps Tripping - 3 Common Reasons (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13073 mb-requirement-id-13083">
        (d) Tell how to find a blown fuse and a tripped circuit breaker in your
        home. Show how to safely reset the circuit breaker. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Lb2UhcnK7n8" target="_blank"
          >How To Identify and Reset a Tripped Circuit Breaker (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13075">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      Make a floor plan wiring diagram of the lights, switches, and outlets for
      a room in your home. Show which fuse or circuit breaker protects each one.
      <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/WJPMY201R-c" target="_blank"
        >How To Wire a Bedroom Diagram (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13059">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 8. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13059 mb-requirement-id-13060">
        (a) Read a meter associated with an electric bill. Determine the total
        power used since the bill, and the cost of that power. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/3G9I1unyOqY" target="_blank"
          >Reading a Digital Electric Meter &amp; Calculate Usage and Cost
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13059 mb-requirement-id-13061">
        (b) Explain other charges on the bill that were taxes or fees. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/2StD-2ERCM0" target="_blank"
          >Here Are the Costs That Affect Your Electricity Bill (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13059 mb-requirement-id-13084">
        (c) Discuss with your counselor five ways your family can conserve
        energy. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/pY6fAYkscTY" target="_blank"
          >Saving Energy at Home - Energy Efficiency Tips (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13068">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 9. </span>
      Explain the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13068 mb-requirement-id-13085">
        (a) Electrical terms - Current, energy, power, resistance, and voltage
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://electricityforum.com/electrical-terms" target="_blank"
          >Electrical Terms Explained (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13068 mb-requirement-id-13086">
        (b) Units of measure - Ampere (amps), ohms, volts, watts, and watt-hours
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/lsef_Vlx83M" target="_blank"
          >The Difference Between Volts, Watts, and Amps - Explained Like You're
          Five (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13068 mb-requirement-id-13087">
        (c) Electrical conditions - Generating source with example, ground, open
        circuit, overvoltage, potential difference, and short circuit <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/v5RJf_V0LYA" target="_blank"
          >Open Circuits, Closed Circuits &amp; Short Circuits - Basic
          Introduction (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/0Ckmt2QyeqQ" target="_blank"
          >What Is Electric Potential Difference? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13068 mb-requirement-id-13088">
        (d) Equipment and their use - circuit, conductor, Ground Fault Circuit
        Interrupter (GFCI), insulator, inverter, rectifier, rheostat,
        substation, surge protection, solar panel, transformer, transmission and
        distribution systems, and wind turbine.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13062">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 10. </span>
      Do TWO of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13062 mb-requirement-id-13063">
        (a) Connect a buzzer, bell, or light with a battery. Have a key or
        switch in the line. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/UWPrhafIUC8" target="_blank"
          >Adding Batteries in Series - Buzzer (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13062 mb-requirement-id-13064">
        (b) Make and run a simple electric motor (from a kit is acceptable, if
        approved by your counselor ahead of time). <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iE01AbIhQhE" target="_blank"
          >Make the Simplest Electric Motor (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13062 mb-requirement-id-13065">
        (c) Build a simple rheostat. Show that it works. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iR3HQR3zu3k" target="_blank"
          >The Rheostat (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13062 mb-requirement-id-13066">
        (d) Build a single-pole, double-throw switch. Show that it works.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/EAvbAiZX2CI" target="_blank"
          >How a Single Pole Double Throw SPDT Switch Works Make and Break
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13062 mb-requirement-id-13067">
        (e) Explain how 3-way switch wiring works in a lighting circuit.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/RKZrg6XKjak" target="_blank"
          >Best Explanation of 3WAY Switching - in Under 3 Minutes! (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13062 mb-requirement-id-13089">
        (f) Connect two lights together in a series circuit along with a battery
        and a switch. Then connect the same circuit in parallel. Discuss the
        differences in the two circuits. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/QKcoDSJSkn0" target="_blank"
          >What Is the Difference Between Series and Parallel Circuits
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13090">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 11. </span>
      Identify three career opportunities that would use skills and knowledge in
      electricity. Pick one and research the training, education, certification
      requirements, experience, and expenses associated with entering the field.
      Research the prospects for employment, starting salary, advancement
      opportunities and career goals associated with this career. Discuss what
      you learned with your counselor and whether you might be interested in
      this career. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a
        href="https://www.tiktok.com/@mal_hoovs/video/7433223621667163438"
        target="_blank"
        >Career Opportunities with an Electrical Engineering Degree (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/Ug9QtgaRplo" target="_blank"
        >Power Plant Operators, Distributors, and Dispatchers Careers (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
